ng conditions in Detroit, Thompson argues, poverty and police brutality continued to plague both neighborhoods and workplaces. Frustration with entrenched discrimination and the lack of meaningful remedies not only led black residents to erupt in the infamous urban uprising of 1967, but it also sparked myriad grassroots challenges to postwar liberalism in the wake of that rebellion.With deft attention to the historical background and to the dramatic struggles of Detroit's residents, and with a new prologue that argues for the ways in which the War on Crime and mass incarceration also devastated the Motor City over time, Thompson has written a biography of an entire nation at a time of crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxMigrationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszMichiganzDetroitxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszMichiganzDetroitxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aLabor movementzMichiganzDetroitxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoorzMichiganzDetroitxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural-urban migrationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban poorzMichiganzDetroitxHistoryy20th century. 4aLabor History. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aAmerica's post-1945 urban crisis.  aDiscrimination.  aascendence of the black power movement.  aauto industry in detroit.  ablack communities.  ablack history in the united states.  ablack history of michigan.  ablood in the water.  abooks about racial policy in detroit.  adeaths in auto plants.  adetroit labor movement.  adetroit politics and government.  adetroit politics.  adetroit urban poor.  adetroit's 1967 rebellion.  adiscrimination in detroit.  adodge revolutionary union movement.  aeconomic conditions in the united 